🔐 DOCS USAGE AND PERMISSIONS
This section focuses on basic user enumeration and permission hardening in Kali Linux.

1️⃣ Identifying System Users
To list all system accounts:
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd
To identify users that have an interactive shell (e.g., /bin/bash):
grep "bin/bash" /etc/passwd

This process helps distinguish between:
System/service accounts
Human users with login capabilities
Understanding which accounts can access the system interactively is essential for security auditing and attack surface reduction.

2️⃣ Privilege Separation
A standard (non-administrative) user account was created to demonstrate separation of privileges.
Key characteristics:
No sudo privileges
Cannot execute administrative commands
Intended strictly for non-privileged tasks
This demonstrates the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) — users should only have the permissions strictly necessary to perform their tasks.

3️⃣ Reviewing Critical File Permissions
Sensitive system files such as:
/etc/shadow
were examined to verify that access is restricted exclusively to the root user.
Proper permission configuration ensures:
Protection of password hashes
Prevention of unauthorized access
Reduced risk of privilege escalation
Correct file ownership and permission management are fundamental components of Linux system hardening.
